{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563961"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:07:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:07:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16919"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16919"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.11,0.1,0.39,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96796"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9609"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79411"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"3642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22688"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96796"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a seven-day history of fevers, tender left ankle, mild headache, and generalised myalgia. She recently returned from a two-week hiking trip in northern Thailand. She has polycystic ovarian syndrome and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. There is a 1 cm black crusted ulcer with surrounding erythema on her left ankle and tender lymphadenopathy in her left groin. A diffuse maculopapular rash is present on her trunk.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cutaneous anthrax","Dengue fever","Melioidosis","Scrub typhus","Spider bite"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of fever, eschar, and regional lymphadenopathy characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Escrub typhus,\u003C/strong\u003E caused by \u003Cem\u003EOrientia (rickettsia) tsutsugamushi\u003C/em\u003E. The disease is transmitted by the bite of larval trombiculid mites (chiggers) in endemic areas of Asia-Pacific - specifically Japan, south east Asia, northern Australia, India and Russia.. The incubation period is typically 6-21 days and diagnosis is typically clinical. Serological confirmation and biopsy can aid diagnosis, however treatment with tetracycline (doxycycline) usually precedes serological confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScrub typhus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, headache, myalgia, and the pathognomonic eschar at the site of the mite bite. Though not always present, the eschar appears as a black, crusted ulcer with surrounding erythema, often accompanied by regional lymphadenopathy. A maculopapular rash may develop later in the illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDengue fever\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever and myalgia but typically includes retro-orbital pain, severe arthralgia, and a characteristic biphasic fever pattern. It does not cause an eschar or regional lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECutaneous anthrax\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a black eschar, but the lesion typically begins as a painless papule that progresses through vesicular and ulcerative stages. It is uncommon in travellers and associated with exposure to infected animals or animal products.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpider bite\u003C/strong\u003E lesions are typically more painful and do not present with the systemic symptoms described. The pattern of regional lymphadenopathy and generalised rash would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelioidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fever and localised skin lesions but typically presents with pneumonia or deep-seated abscesses. The characteristic eschar and regional lymphadenopathy pattern would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Scrub typhus classically presents with fever, eschar, and regional lymphadenopathy after exposure to mite-infested areas.","Early recognition and treatment with doxycycline is essential to prevent complications of scrub typhus."],"references":["Department of Health. Rickettsial Infections. Victoria Department of Health Infectious disease: guidelines and advice. 2015. Available at: https://www.health.vic.gov.au/infectious-diseases/rickettsial-infections","Nicholson W, Paddock C. Rickettsial Disease. Center of Disease Control. 2023. Available at: https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2024/infections-diseases/rickettsial-diseases"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79411"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16919"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79411"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:14:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:14:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9609"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96796"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self"